div.h1: Per-Process Kernel Stack Layout During Context Switch

p.strong: Microscopic view: P1 preempted, P2 running TSS.ESP0 integrity

g.text: THE BUG: Two Processes Sharing ONE Kernel Stack

text.tspan: Each kernel stack = 8 KB = 2 physical pages
Allocated via kmalloc() / static PCB array

g.text: ESP08 CS = 0x0000001B CPU pushed (ring3 code seg)
ESP+00 vec=32 / err=0 pushed by IRQ stub
ESP+04 GS=0x10 / FS=0x10 pushed by irq_common_stub
ESP+08 ES=0x10 / DS=0x10 pushed by irq_common_stub

div.p: ESP+0C pusha block (32 bytes = 8 4B): EDI ESI EBP ESP EBX EDX ECX EAX saved general-purpose register state

g.text: ESP+2C ret_addr irq_return_trampoline context_switch ret target

div.p: P2 currently EXECUTING in kernel (inside sched_schedule / timer IRQ handler) ESP is somewhere here actively being used, not yet saved to PCB
CPU reads esp0 on EVERY interrupt/exception while ring-3 code is executing. Must be updated by tss_set_kernel_stack() before each context switch completes.

g.text: 1. P1 is preempted IRQ pushes frame onto shared stack @ ESP=0xC010_8F00
2. Scheduler runs P2 P2 enters kernel, IRQ uses SAME stack (TSS.ESP0 unchanged)
3. P2's IRQ frame pushed @ ESP=0xC010_8EFC OVERWRITES P1's saved EIP!
4. P1 resumes from corrupted stack iret pops wrong EIP/EFLAGS GPF / triple fault
old_esp = &P2cpu.esp save current ESP into P2 PCB
mov esp, P1cpu.esp NOW ON P1's saved kernel stack
cmp/mov cr3, P1page_directory flush TLB, new address space
ret pops irq_return_trampoline addr from P1's stack
irq_common_stub exit: pop gs/fs/es/ds popa add esp,8 iret
iret pops EIP/CS/EFLAGS/ESP/SS from P1's stack P1 resumes at 0x00401234

text.tspan: CPU reads this on next IRQ
